</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DETROIT 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The nation's Big Three auto makers said today that late-May car and light truck 
sales fell 5.6% from last year, ending the two-month spring buying season that 
saw a flurry of incentives to spark sales. 
</P>
<P>
General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said they sold vehicles 
at a daily rate of 47,359 during from May 21 to 31, compared with a daily rate 
of 50,181 in the same 1988 period. 
</P>
<P>
Car sales were down 4.2% and truck sales were off 7.9%. 
</P>
<P>
The 10-day period last year was one of the strongest of 1988, which proved to 
be the second-best sales year in automobile history. 
