<P>
AT&amp;T AND ITALTEL SIGN BROAD PACT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ROME 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Italian telecommunications equipment maker Italtel today signed an 
agreement with American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. for a far-reaching 
partnership in manufacturing and sales of equipment. 
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, AT&amp;T will acquire 20% of Italtel. In exchange, Italtel's 
parent, the Italian state holding company STET, will take a 20% share of 
AT&amp;T-Network Systems International (ATT-NSI), a joint venture between 
AT&amp;T and Philips NV of the Netherlands. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, AT&amp;T has agreed to make a direct investment of almost $150 
million in Italtel, said an official involved in the deal who requested 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
The accord, which was widely expected, was an important victory for AT&amp;T. 
It allows the U.S. giant access to the ripe Italian telecommunications market, 
which is dominated by Italtel, and improves AT&amp;T's position for the 
post-1992 unified European market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
